sheIgmpSourceIpAddressTable.name: sheIgmpSourceIpAddressTable
sheIgmpSourceIpAddressTable.description: New IGMPv3 configuration with SHE R2.8.

sheIgmpSourceIpAddressEntry.name: sheIgmpSourceIpAddressEntry
sheIgmpSourceIpAddressEntry.description: This is an unordered list of zero or more IP unicast addresses from which multicast reception is possible. An implementation MAY impose a limit on the size of source lists, but that limit MUST NOT be less than 64 addresses per list. When an operation causes the source list size limit to be exceeded, the service interface MUST return an error.

sheIgmpSourceIpIndex.name: sheIgmpSourceIpIndex
sheIgmpSourceIpIndex.description: Table Index. A maximum number of 100 different addresses could be configured inside the NE. These index will be configured in sheIgmpGroupSourceList to select the valid source ip address per group (channel). A default configuration with IP 0.0.0.0 is always available and could not be changed or removed. Only valid for IGMPv3 configuration. New parameter with SHE R2.8.

sheIgmpSourceIpAddress.name: sheIgmpSourceIpAddress
sheIgmpSourceIpAddress.description: This is IP unicast addresses from which multicast reception is possible. If the source IP is 0.0.0.0, it should work as a '*' wildcard configuration (per default available). The configuration is only valid if IGMPv3 is running. New parameter with SHE R2.8.

sheIgmpSourceIpControlStatus.name: sheIgmpSourceIpControlStatus
sheIgmpSourceIpControlStatus.description: The status of a user command.

sheIgmpSourceIpControlIndex.name: sheIgmpSourceIpControlIndex
sheIgmpSourceIpControlIndex.description: A table index used for delete an entry.

sheIgmpSourceIpControlAddress.name: sheIgmpSourceIpControlAddress
sheIgmpSourceIpControlAddress.description: This is IP unicast addresses from which multicast reception is possible. The configuration is only valid if IGMPv3 is running. New parameter with SHE R2.8.

sheIgmpBridgePortProviderConfigTable.name: sheIgmpBridgePortProviderConfigTable
sheIgmpBridgePortProviderConfigTable.description: For the subscriber bridge ports (first table index is sheBridgePortIndex) the table has entries for all multicast provider Vlan a port has currently joined (second table index is sheIgmpProfileVlanVlanId). New supported with SHE R2.8!

sheIgmpBridgePortProviderConfigEntry.name: sheIgmpBridgePortProviderConfigEntry
sheIgmpBridgePortProviderConfigEntry.description: The MCast configuration settiongs per BridgePort.

sheIgmpBridgePortProviderVlanId.name: sheIgmpBridgePortProviderVlanId
sheIgmpBridgePortProviderVlanId.description: MCast Provider VLAN id for the bridge port (second tableindex). New parameter with SHE R2.8.

sheIgmpBridgePortProviderTranslationVlan.name: sheIgmpBridgePortProviderTranslationVlanId
sheIgmpBridgePortProviderTranslationVlan.description: Translation VLAN id for the bridge port. New parameter with SHE R2.8.

sheIgmpBridgePortProviderAllowedVlanIdLi.name: sheIgmpBridgePortProviderAllowedVlanIdList
sheIgmpBridgePortProviderAllowedVlanIdLi.description: The octet string is a list of two octet entries each identifying a sheVlanIndex which is allowed on these bridgeport. The least significant byte is the second octet. The octet string has a variable length of up to 32 octets (max 16 vlan entrys). A entry with 0xffff is a wildCard to indicate that each vlan is allowed. New parameter with SHE R2.8.

sheIgmpBridgePortProviderMcastRemainBand.name: sheIgmpBridgePortProviderMcastRemainBandwith
sheIgmpBridgePortProviderMcastRemainBand.description: It is the bridge port remaining multicast bandwidth per provider. New parameter with SHE R2.8.

sheIgmpBridgePortProviderMcastACStatus.name: sheIgmpBridgePortProviderMcastACStatus
sheIgmpBridgePortProviderMcastACStatus.description: It indicate the bridge port AC (admission control )status per provider. It can be accept or deny. When it is accepted, it indicates the provider still has enough bandwidth for multicast access. When it is denied, it indicates the provider is short of bandwidth for multicast access. 1 means accept, 0 means deny New parameter with SHE R2.8.

sheQueuePriorityTable.description: Configure the .1p prioritys of each queue for upstream and downstream direction.

sheQueuePriority.description: The index of that table. It represents the .1p Priority + 1,because priority values will have a range from 0-7 but index has to start always with 1.

sheQueueNumber.name: sheQueueNumber
sheQueueNumber.description: That represents the Queue-Number. Only applicable for ingress queues on iu, because cxu_b will always use only one queue for traffic.

sheReducedQueuePriorityTable.name: sheReducedQueuePriorityTable
sheReducedQueuePriorityTable.description: There could a shrinking of queues on the iu in downstream direction (depending on the used IU type). So the available .1p-prioritys has to be mapped on a set of only four available queue-numbers.

sheReducedQueuePriority.name: sheReducedQueuePriority
sheReducedQueuePriority.description: The index of that table. It represents the .1p Priority + 1,because priority values will have a range from 0-7 but index has to start always with 1.

sheReducedQueueNumber.name: sheReducedQueueNumber
sheReducedQueueNumber.description: Number of the outgoing queue, where this priority is mapped on.

sheQueueModeInterfaceTypeIndex.description: Describes the interface type, were this queue configuration should be used. uplink downlink cascading subcascading

sheQueueConfigurationMode.name: sheQueueConfigurationMode
sheQueueConfigurationMode.description: Describes the queue mode, for this interface type. strict weighted Note: Mode 'weighted' could mean 'weighted round robin' (wrr) or 'weighted fair queueing' (wfq) and depends on the individual HW restrictions of the used board's.

sheQueueWeightTable.name: sheQueueWeightTable
sheQueueWeightTable.description: Configure weight's of queues for upstream direction.

sheQueueIndex.name: sheQueueIndex
sheQueueIndex.description: A table index. This index represents the Queue-Number.

sheQueueWeight.name: sheQueueWeight
sheQueueWeight.description: A weight value for queue if mode is not strict. Depending on used HW (CXU types, IU types) works not on all interface types. Weights are interpreted not as absolute values but only in relation to the sum of the weights of all queues. If a weight of a queue is set to 100, this queue will work in 'strict' mode against lower prio queues again.

sheQueueWeightWatermarkLow.name: sheQueueWeightWatermarkLow
sheQueueWeightWatermarkLow.description: A low watermark value for a NE internal color aware queue handling. This value represents a % - Value of usage of the total Queue-Size. Default values: ------------------- Queue | Low | ------------------- 1 | 20 % | 2 | 20 % | 3 | 20 % | 4 | 20 % | 5 | 30 % | 6 | 30 % | 7 | 15 % | 8 | 15 % |

sheQueueWeightWatermarkHigh.name: sheQueueWeightWatermarkHigh
sheQueueWeightWatermarkHigh.description: A high watermark value for a NE internal color aware queue handling. High watermark defines additional the total used queue size as %-value of the theoretical possible queue size. Default Values: ------------ Queue | High ------------ 1 | 30 % 2 | 30 % 3 | 30 % 4 | 30 % 5 | 40 % 6 | 40 % 7 | 20 % 8 | 20 %

sheQueueWeightControlStatus.name: sheQueueWeightControlStatus
sheQueueWeightControlStatus.description: The status of a user command.

sheQueueWeightControlTimer.name: sheQueueWeightControlTimer
sheQueueWeightControlTimer.description: The maximum wait time for the manager for a long running user command.

sheQueueWeightControlTimeStamp.name: sheQueueWeightControlTimeStamp
sheQueueWeightControlTimeStamp.description: The time stamp of the last command (end of command).

sheQueueWeightControlWatermarkLow.name: sheQueueWeightControlWatermarkLow
sheQueueWeightControlWatermarkLow.description: Not needed for configuration in current scenario. This value represents a % - Value of usage of the total Queue-Size.

sheQueueWeightControlWatermarkHigh.name: sheQueueWeightControlWatermarkHigh
sheQueueWeightControlWatermarkHigh.description: Not needed for configuration in current scenario.This value represents a % - Value of usage of the total Queue-Size.

sheCardQueueEntryDeleted.description: Delete the queue handling for a card.

sheCardQueueEntryConfigResult.name: sheCardQueueEntryConfigResult
sheCardQueueEntryConfigResult.description: Result trap for long running command to configure the queue handling for a card.

sheCardQueueConfigurationTable.name: sheCardQueueConfigurationTable
sheCardQueueConfigurationTable.description: Configure the queue handling individuell per configured card. This will replace the general queue configuration settings. Per default, no indivudell settings are made and this table is empty (could be change during development). NEW supported with R2.8!

sheCardQueueConfigurationEntry.name: sheCardQueueConfigurationEntry
sheCardQueueConfigurationEntry.description: One entry for each card, if these card should not use the global NE queue configuration parameters. If a card type will never uses the global NE parameters, a entry for this card will be automatically created during card creation process. This table uses two indices: First index is the entPhysicalIndex from entPhysicalTable for the card. Second index is sheCardQueueInterfaceTypeIndex from this table.

sheCardQueueInterfaceTypeIndex.name: sheCardQueueInterfaceTypeIndex
sheCardQueueInterfaceTypeIndex.description: Describes the interface type, were this queue configuration should be used. Valid values for this configuration's are: uplink(1) -> for central board means uplink, for IU means interlink to cxu downlink(2) -> for central board means interlink to IU's, for IU means subcriber

sheCardQueueSchedulingMode.name: sheCardQueueSchedulingMode
sheCardQueueSchedulingMode.description: Describes the queue scheduling mode. strict weighted Note: Mode 'weighted' could mean 'weighted round robin' (wrr) or 'weighted fair queueing' (wfq) and depends on the individual HW restrictions of the used board's.

sheCardQueue1Weight.name: sheCardQueue1Weight
sheCardQueue1Weight.description: A weight value for queue 1 if mode is not strict. Depending on used HW (CXU types, IU types) works not on all interface types. Weights are interpreted not as absolute values but only in relation to the sum of the weights of all queues. If a weight of a queue is set to 100, this queue will work in 'strict' mode against lower prio queues again.

sheCardQueue1Watermarks.name: sheCardQueue1Watermarks
sheCardQueue1Watermarks.description: A watermark configuration for a NE internal colour aware queue handling for queue number 1. The lower two octets representing the low watermark and the higher two octets the high watermark value. This value's represents a % - value of usage of the total Queue-Size. Example: 0x00500032 -> high watermark = 0x0050 = 80% -> low watermark = 0x0032 = 50% The maximum value for a single watermark is 0x0064 = 100 %. The high watermark defines additional the total used queue size as %-value of the theoretical possible queue size.

sheCardQueue4Watermarks.name: sheCardQueue4Watermarks
sheCardQueue4Watermarks.description: A watermark configuration for a NE internal colour aware queue handling for queue number 4. The lower two octets representing the low watermark and the higher two octets the high watermark value. This value's represents a % - value of usage of the total Queue-Size. Example: 0x00500032 -> high watermark = 0x0050 = 80% -> low watermark = 0x0032 = 50% The maximum value for a single watermark is 0x0064 = 100 %. The high watermark defines additional the total used queue size as %-value of the theoretical possible queue size.

sheCardQueue5Weight.name: sheCardQueue5Weight
sheCardQueue5Weight.description: A weight value for queue 5 if mode is not strict. Depending on used HW (CXU types, IU types) works not on all interface types. Weights are interpreted not as absolute values but only in relation to the sum of the weights of all queues. If a weight of a queue is set to 100, this queue will work in 'strict' mode against lower prio queues again.

sheCardQueue5Watermarks.name: sheCardQueue5Watermarks
sheCardQueue5Watermarks.description: A watermark configuration for a NE internal colour aware queue handling for queue number 5. The lower two octets representing the low watermark and the higher two octets the high watermark value. This value's represents a % - value of usage of the total Queue-Size. Depending on the card type,these configuration could have no effect!! Example: 0x00500032 -> high watermark = 0x0050 = 80% -> low watermark = 0x0032 = 50% The maximum value for a single watermark is 0x0064 = 100 %. The high watermark defines additional the total used queue size as %-value of the theoretical possible queue size.

sheCardQueueColourAwareTCSource.name: sheCardQueueColourAwareTCSource
sheCardQueueColourAwareTCSource.description: Configure, how the current traffic class of a frame should detected. Valid values: none(0), dscp(2), providerBridge(4) Configuration will be currently ignored! Starting support planed for R3.5!

sheCardQueueColourMarking.name: sheCardQueueColourMarking
sheCardQueueColourMarking.description: Configure, if and how the current colour should be marked. Colour marking will only work in upstream direction. Valid values: none(0), dscp(2), providerBridge(4) Configuration will be currently ignored! Starting support planed for 3.5!

sheCardQueueDiscardPolicy.name: sheCardQueueDiscardPolicy
sheCardQueueDiscardPolicy.description: Describes the policy in case of frame discards. Possible values: tailDrop(1), wRed(2) Configuration will be currently ignored! Starting support planed for R3.5!

sheCardQueueMode.name: sheCardQueueMode
sheCardQueueMode.description: This parameter describe the general queue mode for this card. Depending on the used card type not all modes are available. modeHQS will only be supported by DSL cards with Convergate chipset and only in downstream direction. mode8QueueFlat will only be supported by VDSL2 and Shdsl2 cards and only in downstream direction. mode4QueueFlat(1) -> 4 queues per port mode8QueueFlat(2) -> 8 queues per port modeHQS(3) -> 8 queues with hierarchical queuing and scheduling. New parameter with R2.8.

sheCardQueueHqsSecondStageInputQueue.name: sheCardQueueHqsSecondStageInputQueue
sheCardQueueHqsSecondStageInputQueue.description: This parameter is only valid for queuemode 'modeHQS' and is don't care for the others. The queue of the second level scheduler (queuenumbers 5-8) in which the frames of the first level scheduler will be enqueued could be selected here. New parameter with R2.8.

sheCardQueueHqsFirstStagePir.name: sheCardQueueHqsFirstStagePir
sheCardQueueHqsFirstStagePir.description: This parameter configures the peek information rate of the first stage scheduler if queuemode modeHQS is running. Otherwise don't care. Note: The PIR of the first level queuing block should not be higher than the emission rate of the respective second level queue into which the first level queues are enqueued. The given value could be adapted (rounded) in the NE to fullfill different HW dependencies. That will not shown here. For example, IU's with Convergate chipset will round the configured value to multiples of 1 kByte/s. New parameter with R2.8.

sheCardQueueHqsFirstStagePbs.name: sheCardQueueHqsFirstStagePbs
sheCardQueueHqsFirstStagePbs.description: This parameter configures the peek burst size of the first stage scheduler if queuemode modeHQS is running. Otherwise don't care. New parameter with R2.8.

sheCardQueueControlRequest.name: sheCardQueueControlRequest
sheCardQueueControlRequest.description: configureCardQueueConfigurationEntry: sheCardQueueConfigurationControlIndex sheCardQueueControlInterfaceTypeIndex ... deleteCardQueueConfigurationEntry: sheCardQueueConfigurationControlIndex sheCardQueueControlInterfaceTypeIndex

sheCardQueueControlIndex.name: sheCardQueueControlIndex
sheCardQueueControlIndex.description: The first index (entPhysicalIndex of card) to identify the table-entry to be configured.

sheCardQueueControlStatus.name: sheCardQueueControlStatus
sheCardQueueControlStatus.description: The status of a user command.

sheCardQueueControlTimer.name: sheCardQueueControlTimer
sheCardQueueControlTimer.description: The maximum wait time for the manager for a long running user command.

sheCardQueueControlReqResult.name: sheCardQueueControlReqResult
sheCardQueueControlReqResult.description: The result of the last user command.

sheCardQueueControlTimeStamp.name: sheCardQueueControlTimeStamp
sheCardQueueControlTimeStamp.description: The time stamp of the last command (end of command).

sheCardQueueControlInterfaceTypeIndex.name: sheCardQueueControlInterfaceTypeIndex
sheCardQueueControlInterfaceTypeIndex.description: The second index to identify the table-entry to be configured.

sheCardQueueControlMode.name: sheCardQueueControlMode
sheCardQueueControlMode.description: This parameter set the general queue mode for this card. Depending on the used card type not all modes are available. modeHQS will only be supported by DSL cards with Convergate chipset and only in downstream direction. mode8QueueFlat will only be supported by VDSL2 and Shdsl2 cards and only in downstream direction. mode4QueueFlat(1) -> 4 queues per port mode8QueueFlat(2) -> 8 queues per port modeHQS(3) -> 8 queues with hierarchical queuing and scheduling. New parameter with R2.8.

sheCardQueueControlHqsSecondStageInputQu.name: sheCardQueueControlHqsSecondStageInputQueue
sheCardQueueControlHqsSecondStageInputQu.description: This parameter is only valid for queuemode 'modeHQS' and is don't care for the others. The queue of the second level scheduler (queuenumbers 1-4) in which the frames of the first level scheduler will be enqueued could be selected here. New parameter with R2.8.

sheCardQueueControlHqsFirstStagePir.name: sheCardQueueControlHqsFirstStagePir
sheCardQueueControlHqsFirstStagePir.description: This parameter configures the peek information rate of the first stage scheduler if queuemode modeHQS is running. Otherwise don't care. Note: The PIR of the first level queuing block should not be higher than the emission rate of the respective second level queue into which the first level queues are enqueued. The given value could be adapted (rounded) in the NE to fullfill different HW dependencies. That will not shown here. For example, IU's with Convergate chipset will round the configured value to multiples of 1 kByte/s. New parameter with R2.8.

sheCardQueueControlHqsFirstStagePbs.name: sheCardQueueControlHqsFirstStagePbs
sheCardQueueControlHqsFirstStagePbs.description: This parameter configures the peek burst size of the first stage scheduler if queuemode modeHQS is running. Otherwise don't care. New parameter with R2.8.

sheShapingProfileEntry.name: sheShapingProfileEntry
sheShapingProfileEntry.description: One entry for each shaping profile. Selection of the used profile will be done via ShapingProfileAssignmentTable.

sheShapingProfileName.name: sheShapingProfileName
sheShapingProfileName.description: A descriptional name for this Shaping profile. Spaces and other special characters (: o) are not allowed!!

sheShapingProfileCir.name: sheShapingProfileCir
sheShapingProfileCir.description: The Committed Information Rate for downstream shaping.

sheShapingProfileCbs.name: sheShapingProfileCbs
sheShapingProfileCbs.description: The Committed Burst Size for downstream shaping.

sheShapingProfileControlRequest.name: sheShapingProfileControlRequest
sheShapingProfileControlRequest.description: createShapingProfile: sheShapingProfileControlName sheShapingProfileControlCir sheShapingProfileControlCbs deleteShapingProfile: sheShapingProfileControlIndex modifyShapingProfile: sheShapingProfileControlIndex sheShapingProfileControlName sheShapingProfileControlCir sheShapingProfileControlCbs

sheShapingProfileControlIndex.name: sheShapingProfileControlIndex
sheShapingProfileControlIndex.description: Index of the configured table entry. Needed for modify or delete.

sheShapingProfileControlStatus.name: sheShapingProfileControlStatus
sheShapingProfileControlStatus.description: The status of a user command.

sheShapingProfileControlTimer.name: sheShapingProfileControlTimer
sheShapingProfileControlTimer.description: The maximum wait time for the manager for a long running user command.

sheShapingProfileControlReqResult.name: sheShapingProfileControlReqResult
sheShapingProfileControlReqResult.description: The result of the last user command.

sheShapingProfileControlTimeStamp.name: sheShapingProfileControlTimeStamp
sheShapingProfileControlTimeStamp.description: The time stamp of the last command (end of command).

sheShapingProfileControlProfileName.name: sheShapingProfileControlProfileName
sheShapingProfileControlProfileName.description: look at ShapingProfileTable... Spaces and other special characters (: o) are not allowed!!

sheShapingProfileAssignmentEntry.name: sheShapingProfileAssignmentEntry
sheShapingProfileAssignmentEntry.description: One entry for each assigned shaping profile. The assignment will use two indeces. First index is the ifIndex of the used subscriber port. Second index is the queue number. New with R2.8: There are two special values for queuenumber are supported, which allow to assign such a shaping profile to the lower (1..4) or upper (5..8) queue-group. If mode4QueueFlat is running, only the lower group is available. One shaping profile for all queues in queuemode mode8QueueFlat or modeHqs is not supported.

sheShapingProfileAssignmentQueueNumber.name: sheShapingProfileAssignmentQueueNumber
sheShapingProfileAssignmentQueueNumber.description: The second index of this table. That represents the used Queue-Number for this ShapingProfile assignment. Note: Depending on the used card type, the number of available queues could be restricted to 4. An assignment to 8 queues will always be possible and the IU will then ignore the upper 4 queue configurations. New with R2.8: Two special values allow the assignment of a shapingProfile to a group of queues for this DSL-port and not only to a single queue of this port. '0' will assign this to the DSL port. For IU_CG boards, this is not fully supported in queue mode 'mode8QueueFlat'. Here this setting will only apply to the higher prio queue group (queue 5..8). Additionally a specific shaper should be configured for the lower prio queue group (queue 1..4) with value '255'.

sheShapingProfileAssignmentProfileIndex.name: sheShapingProfileAssignmentProfileIndex
sheShapingProfileAssignmentProfileIndex.description: This value represents a valid index from sheShapingProfileTable which should be used for this DSL-Port and Queue-Number.

sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlIndex.name: sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlIndex
sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlIndex.description: ifIndex of the DSL-Interface where a shaping profile should be assigned. First index value for assignment.

sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlStatus.name: sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlStatus
sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlStatus.description: The status of a user command.

sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlTimer.name: sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlTimer
sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlTimer.description: The maximum wait time for the manager for a long running user command.

sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlReqRes.name: sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlReqResult
sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlReqRes.description: The result of the last user command.

sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlTimeSt.name: sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlTimeStamp
sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlTimeSt.description: The time stamp of the last command (end of command).

sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlQueueN.name: sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlQueueNumber
sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlQueueN.description: QueueNumber of the DSL-Interface where a shaping profile should be assigned. Second index value for assignment. New with R2.8: Two special values allow the assignment of a shapingProfile to a group of queues for this DSL-port and not only to a single queue of this port. '0' will assign this to the DSL port. For IU_CG boards, this is not fully supported in queue mode 'mode8QueueFlat'. Here this setting will only apply to the higher prio queue group (queue 5..8). Additionally a specific shaper should be configured for the lower prio queue group (queue 1..4) with value '255'.

sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlProfil.name: sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlProfileIndex
sheShapingProfileAssignmentControlProfil.description: This value represents a valid index from sheShapingProfileTable which should be used for this DSL-Port and Queue-Number.

sheShapingProfileCreated.name: sheShapingProfileCreated
sheShapingProfileCreated.description: Configuration notification. A new shaping profile was created in sheShapingProfileTable.

sheShapingProfileModified.name: sheShapingProfileModified
sheShapingProfileModified.description: Configuration notification. A shaping profile was modified in sheShapingProfileTable.

sheShapingProfileDeleted.name: sheShapingProfileDeleted
sheShapingProfileDeleted.description: Configuration notification. A shaping profile was deleted from sheShapingProfileTable.

sheShapingProfileAssigned.name: sheShapingProfileAssigned
sheShapingProfileAssigned.description: Configuration notification. A shaping profile from sheShapingProfileTable was assigned to port.queuenumber.

sheShapingProfileAssignmentDeleted.name: sheShapingProfileAssignmentDeleted
sheShapingProfileAssignmentDeleted.description: Configuration notification. An existing shaping profile assignment was deleted from sheShapingProfileAssignmentTable.

sheErpDomainTrafficVlan.name: sheErpDomainTrafficVlan
sheErpDomainTrafficVlan.description: This octet string with 4096 octets maps payload VLANs to ERP domains: one octet containing the sheErpDomainIndex per VLAN. The octet number is the sheVlanIndex. You can assign a VLAN to only one ERP domain at a time. In this way the ERP domains of the sheErpDomainTable can be used on a per-VLAN basis. The value 0 indicates that no ERP domain is assigned to that VLAN.

sheErpBaseControlRequest.name: sheErpBaseControlRequest
sheErpBaseControlRequest.description: A SetRequest on this attribute starts a command execution process in the NetElement. - modifyErpDomainTrafficVlan parameters: sheErpBaseControlDomainTrafficVlan

sheErpBaseControlStatus.name: sheErpBaseControlStatus
sheErpBaseControlStatus.description: Describes the status of a user command group, used for block commands while a command execution is in process. Values : idle, busy, passed, failed. idle: default, no command in process busy: command execution in process, attempts to start another user command on this control block are rejected passed/failed: status at end of command

sheErpBaseControlTimestamp.name: sheErpBaseControlTimestamp
sheErpBaseControlTimestamp.description: Time stamp attribute set at the end of a command.

sheErpBaseControlTimer.name: sheErpBaseControlTimer
sheErpBaseControlTimer.description: Maximum command execution time (timeout) in seconds in case of a long running command.

sheErpBaseControlDomainTrafficVlan.name: sheErpBaseControlDomainTrafficVlan
sheErpBaseControlDomainTrafficVlan.description: This octet string with 4096 octets maps payload VLANs to ERP domains: one octet containing the sheErpDomainIndex per VLAN. The octet number is the sheVlanIndex. You can assign a VLAN to only one ERP domain at a time. In this way the ERP domains of the sheErpDomainTable can be used on a per-VLAN basis. The value 0 indicates that no ERP domain is assigned to that VLAN. parameter for - modifyErpDomainTrafficVlan

sheErpDomainTable.name: sheErpDomainTable
sheErpDomainTable.description: ERP domains configuration table with static entries.

sheErpDomainIndex.name: sheErpDomainIndex
sheErpDomainIndex.description: An index value that uniquely identifies an ERP domain.

sheErpDomainName.name: sheErpDomainName
sheErpDomainName.description: The associated name of the ERP Domain. Spaces and other special characters (: o) are not allowed!!

sheErpDomainPrimaryPort.name: sheErpDomainPrimaryPort
sheErpDomainPrimaryPort.description: The sheBridgePortIndex of the sheBridgePortTable that represents the primary port of the ERP domain. The allowed range is 1-65535. Only Ethernet interfaces possible. The value -1 is used to indicate that it is unassigned (Invalid).

sheErpDomainSecondaryPort.name: sheErpDomainSecondaryPort
sheErpDomainSecondaryPort.description: The sheBridgePortIndex of the sheBridgePortTable that represents the secondary port of the ERP domain. The allowed range is 1-65535. Only Ethernet interfaces possible. The value -1 is used to indicate that it is unassigned (Invalid).

sheErpDomainWaitToRestoreTime.name: sheErpDomainWaitToRestoreTime
sheErpDomainWaitToRestoreTime.description: Time in seconds taken to verify that ring integrity is maintained before switch to Idle state after all links have recovered from Link Failure, Link Degrade or Loss of Test Packet. Range 2..720.

sheErpDomainTestPacketInterval.name: sheErpDomainTestPacketInterval
sheErpDomainTestPacketInterval.description: Time interval , in milliseconds, between consecutive transmission of test packets. The Test Packet Interval is used to define the time to initiate protection due to Loss of Test Packets, The value of Test Packet Interval is between 10 ms and 500 ms in 10 ms steps.

sheErpDomainLearningDisabledTime.name: sheErpDomainLearningDisabledTime
sheErpDomainLearningDisabledTime.description: Configures the time during which learning is disabled after a FDB flush. The learning is only disabled for the protected VLAN of the domain on the ERP ports. The value of the Learning Disabled Time is between 0 and 500 ms in steps of 10 ms.

sheErpDomainProtectionActivation.name: sheErpDomainProtectionActivation
sheErpDomainProtectionActivation.description: Represents if ERP Protection activation is activated or deactivated (admin state). When the ERP domain is activated the ERP process will start running. All alarms/traps are cleared and the ERP protection state is reported as unknown. The domain will enter deactivated state. The ERP protection activation default value is deactivated. deny(0) - protection inactive permit(1) - protection active

sheErpDomainOperatorRequest.name: sheErpDomainOperatorRequest
sheErpDomainOperatorRequest.description: Two operators requests are possible for one ERP domain. For Normal nodes operator requests are ignored. manualToSecondary(1) - Manual Switch to Secondary port - This command enables to swap the roles of primary and secondary port on the RM Node. clear(2) - Clear - This command disables a previous Manual Switch to Secondary port.

sheErpDomainNodeMode.name: sheErpDomainNodeMode
sheErpDomainNodeMode.description: An ERP domain may operate in two modes. RM Node or Normal Node. The description of these two modes is included in ERP concept specification. Only one node per domain could be a rm node. normalNode(1) rmNode(2)

sheErpDomainControlVlan.name: sheErpDomainControlVlan
sheErpDomainControlVlan.description: Represents the VLAN ID sheVlanIndex of the control VLAN of the domain. The control VLAN may not be used in other domains as control VLAN or as protected VLAN. The control VLAN must be a VLAN with a high priority QoS profile.

sheErpDomainNodeStatus.name: sheErpDomainNodeStatus
sheErpDomainNodeStatus.description: Reflects the domain node status. rmIdle(1) primaryProtecting(2) protecting(3) idle(4) failed-S(5) failed-P(6) preForward(7) isolated(8) deactivated(9) backoff(10)

sheErpDomainRingStatus.name: sheErpDomainRingStatus
sheErpDomainRingStatus.description: Actual protection state of the ERP domain on the ring. The following three states are defined: Normal - All ring nodes are available and used. Protecting - At least one Link on the ring is failed. Unknown - This state is used when the ERP protection is not activated, or when the Multiple Failures are detected in a Normal Node.

sheErpDomainLotp.name: sheErpDomainLotp
sheErpDomainLotp.description: Erp domain Loss of Test Packet alarm status. Only meaningful for RM nodes. true(1) - alarm active false(2) - alarm inactive

sheErpDomainUlotp.name: sheErpDomainUlotp
sheErpDomainUlotp.description: Erp domain Unidirectional Detection of Loss of Test Packet alarm status. Only meaningful for RM nodes. true(1) - alarm active false(2) - alarm inactive

sheErpDomainMultipleRm.name: sheErpDomainMultipleRm
sheErpDomainMultipleRm.description: Erp domain Multiple Redundancy Manager alarm status. Only meaningful for RM nodes. true(1) - alarm active false(2) - alarm inactive

sheErpDomainRmReach.name: sheErpDomainRmReach
sheErpDomainRmReach.description: RM Node reacheability alarm status. Erp domain detection of mutiple failures in the ring cause the RM Node to become unreacheable to this normal node (only meaningful for normal nodes). true(1) - RM Node is unreacheable, alarm active false(2) - RM Node is reacheable, alarm inactive

sheErpDomainLotpTrapEnable.name: sheErpDomainLotpTrapEnable
sheErpDomainLotpTrapEnable.description: Erp domain Loss of Test Packet Trap. Configures sending OF LOTP traps when detected by the RM node. deny(0) permit(1)

sheErpDomainUlotpTrapEnable.name: sheErpDomainUlotpTrapEnable
sheErpDomainUlotpTrapEnable.description: Erp domain Unidirectional Loss of Test Packet Trap. Configures sending of ULOTP traps when detected by the RM node. deny(0) permit(1)

sheErpDomainMultipleRmTrapEnable.name: sheErpDomainMultipleRmTrapEnable
sheErpDomainMultipleRmTrapEnable.description: Erp domain multiple RM nodes Trap. Configures sending of MultipleRM traps when detected by the RM node. deny(0) permit(1)

sheErpDomainRmReachTrapEnable.name: sheErpDomainRmReachTrapEnable
sheErpDomainRmReachTrapEnable.description: Erp domain multiple failures trap. Configures sending of RMNodeReacheablility traps when detected by the normal node. deny(0) permit(1)

sheErpDomainAlarmSeverityIndex.name: sheErpDomainAlarmSeverityIndex
sheErpDomainAlarmSeverityIndex.description: Index to the AlarmSeverityProfileTable. Defines the actual AlarmSeverities for all alarms per ERP domain.

sheErpDomainControlRequest.name: sheErpDomainControlRequest
sheErpDomainControlRequest.description: A SetRequest on this attribute starts a command execution process in the NetElement. modifyErpDomainEntry(826) parameters: - sheErpDomainControlDomainIndex - sheErpDomainControlDomainName - sheErpDomainControlDomainPrimaryPort - sheErpDomainControlDomainSecondaryPort - sheErpDomainControlWaitToRestoreTime - sheErpDomainControlTestPacketInterval - sheErpDomainControlLearningDisabledTime - sheErpDomainControlDomainNodeMode - sheErpDomainControlDomainControlVlan - sheErpDomainControlLotpTrapEnable - sheErpDomainControlUlotpTrapEnable - sheErpDomainControlMultipleRmTrapEnable - sheErpDomainControlRmReachTrapEnable - sheErpDomainControlAlarmSeverityIndex activateErpDomain(827) - sheErpDomainControlDomainIndex - sheErpDomainControlProtectionActivation operatorRequestErpDomain(828) - sheErpDomainControlDomainIndex - sheErpDomainControlOperatorRequest

sheErpDomainControlStatus.name: sheErpDomainControlStatus
sheErpDomainControlStatus.description: Describes the status of a user command group, used for block commands while a command execution is in process. Values : idle, busy, passed, failed. idle: default, no command in process busy: command execution in process, attempts to start another user command on this control block are rejected passed/failed: status at end of command

sheErpDomainControlTimestamp.name: sheErpDomainControlTimestamp
sheErpDomainControlTimestamp.description: Time stamp attribute set at the end of a command.

sheErpDomainControlTimer.name: sheErpDomainControlTimer
sheErpDomainControlTimer.description: Maximum command execution time (timeout) in seconds in case of a long running command.

sheErpDomainControlDomainIndex.name: sheErpDomainControlDomainIndex
sheErpDomainControlDomainIndex.description: An index value that uniquely identifies an ERP domain. parameter for - modifyErpDomainEntry - modifyErpDomainTraps - activateErpDomain - operatorRequestErpDomain

sheErpDomainControlDomainName.name: sheErpDomainControlDomainName
sheErpDomainControlDomainName.description: The associated name of the ERP Domain. Spaces and other special characters (: o) are not allowed!! parameter for - modifyErpDomainEntry

sheErpDomainControlDomainPrimaryPort.name: sheErpDomainControlDomainPrimaryPort
sheErpDomainControlDomainPrimaryPort.description: The sheBridgePortIndex of the sheBridgePortTable that represents the primary port of the ERP domain. The allowed range is 1-65535. Only Ethernet interfaces possible. The value -1 is used to indicate that it is unassigned (Invalid). parameter for - modifyErpDomainEntry

sheErpDomainControlDomainSecondaryPort.name: sheErpDomainControlDomainSecondaryPort
sheErpDomainControlDomainSecondaryPort.description: The sheBridgePortIndex of the sheBridgePortTable that represents the secondary port of the ERP domain. The allowed range is 1-65535. Only Ethernet interfaces possible. The value -1 is used to indicate that it is unassigned (Invalid). parameter for - modifyErpDomainEntry

sheErpDomainControlWaitToRestoreTime.name: sheErpDomainControlWaitToRestoreTime
sheErpDomainControlWaitToRestoreTime.description: Time in seconds taken to verify that ring integrity is maintained before switch to Idle state after all links have recovered from Link Failure, Link Degrade or Loss of Test Packet. parameter for - modifyErpDomainEntry

sheErpDomainControlTestPacketInterval.name: sheErpDomainControlTestPacketInterval
sheErpDomainControlTestPacketInterval.description: Time interval , in milliseconds, between consecutive transmission of test packets. The Test Packet Interval is used to define the time to initiate protection due to Loss of Test Packets, The value of Test Packet Interval is between 10 ms and 500 ms in 10 ms steps. parameter for - modifyErpDomainEntry

sheErpDomainControlLearningDisabledTime.name: sheErpDomainControlLearningDisabledTime
sheErpDomainControlLearningDisabledTime.description: Configures the time during which learning is disabled after a FDB flush. The learning is only disabled for the protected VLAN of the domain on the ERP ports. The value of the Learning Disabled Time is between 0 and 500 ms in steps of 10 ms. parameter for - modifyErpDomainEntry

sheErpDomainControlProtectionActivation.name: sheErpDomainControlProtectionActivation
sheErpDomainControlProtectionActivation.description: Represents if ERP Protection activation is activated or deactivated. When the ERP domain is activated the ERP process will start running. All alarms/traps are cleared and the ERP protection state is reported as unknown. The domain will enter deactivated state. The ERP protection activation default value is deactivated. deny(0) - protection inactive permit(1) - protection active parameter for - activateErpDomain

sheErpDomainControlOperatorRequest.name: sheErpDomainControlOperatorRequest
sheErpDomainControlOperatorRequest.description: Two operators requests are possible for one ERP domain. For Normal nodes operator requests are ignored. manualToSecondary(1) - Manual Switch to Secondary port - This command enables to swap the roles of primary and secondary port on the RM Node. clear(2) - Clear - This command disables a previous Manual Switch to Secondary port. parameter for - operatorRequestErpDomain

sheErpDomainControlDomainNodeMode.name: sheErpDomainControlDomainNodeMode

sheBcscTable.description: This table has one entry for each combination of port or vlan and traffic type where broadcast storm control has to be performed.

sheBcscEntry.name: sheBcscEntry
sheBcscEntry.description: Specifies per port or vlan and per traffic type the broadcast storm control parameters, i.e. how many packets/bits per second can be received.

sheBcscType.description: Broadcast storm control traffic type. 1 - Broadcast 2 - Multicast 3 - Destination Lookup Failure (unicast)

sheBcscConfigIndex.description: Index of the controlled entity. In case of port scope, it should be sheBridgePortIndex of the sheBridgePortTable and the allowed range is 1-65535. In case of vlan scope, it should be sheVlanIndex of the sheVlanTable and the allowed range is 1-4093.

sheBcscThresholdValue.name: sheBcscThresholdValue
sheBcscThresholdValue.description: Maximum traffic amount of type sheBcscThresholdType. If the threshold of a traffic type is reached within the 1 second measuring interval, further traffic of that type is dropped during the next time period. The switch continues to monitor traffic on the port, and when the utilization level is below the threshold level, the type of traffic that was dropped is forwarded again during the next time period.

sheMstpBaseConfName.name: sheMstpBaseConfName
sheMstpBaseConfName.description: The MST configuration determines to which MST region Spaces and other special characters (: o) are not allowed!! each switch belongs. The configuration includes the name of the region, the revision number, and the MST instance-to-VLAN assignment map. For two or more switches to be in the same MST region, they must have the same VLAN-to-instance mapping, the same configuration revision number, and the same name.

sheMstpBaseRevisionLevel.name: sheMstpBaseRevisionLevel
sheMstpBaseRevisionLevel.description: The MST configuration determines to which MST region each switch belongs. The configuration includes the name of the region, the revision number, and the MST instance-to-VLAN assignment map. For two or more switches to be in the same MST region, they must have the same VLAN-to-instance mapping, the same configuration revision number, and the same name. The range of the revision number is 0 to 65535.

sheMstpBaseConfIdVlanIdList.name: sheMstpBaseConfIdVlanIdList
sheMstpBaseConfIdVlanIdList.description: The MST configuration determines to which MST region each switch belongs. The configuration includes the name of the region, the revision number, and the MST instance-to-VLAN assignment map. For two or more switches to be in the same MST region, they must have the same VLAN-to-instance mapping, the same configuration revision number, and the same name. The sheMstpBridgeProtoParamTable holds 32 static profile entries of spanning tree protocol parameters. A profile can be used on a per-VLAN basis. This octet String with 4096 octets maps VLANs to spanning tree protocol profiles: one octet containing the sheMstpBridgeProtoParamIndex per VLAN. The octet number is the sheVlanIndex. You can assign a VLAN to only one spanning-tree instance at a time.

sheMstpBaseControlRevisionLevel.name: sheMstpBaseControlRevisionLevel
sheMstpBaseControlRevisionLevel.description: The MST configuration determines to which MST region each switch belongs. The configuration includes the name of the region, the revision number, and the MST instance-to-VLAN assignment map. For two or more switches to be in the same MST region, they must have the same VLAN-to-instance mapping, the same configuration revision number, and the same name. The range of the revision number is 0 to 65535. parameter of - modifyMstpBaseConfig

sheMstpBaseControlConfIdVlanIdList.name: sheMstpBaseControlConfIdVlanIdList
sheMstpBaseControlConfIdVlanIdList.description: The MST configuration determines to which MST region each switch belongs. The configuration includes the name of the region, the revision number, and the MST instance-to-VLAN assignment map. For two or more switches to be in the same MST region, they must have the same VLAN-to-instance mapping, the same configuration revision number, and the same name. The sheMstpBridgeProtoParamTable holds 32 static profile entries of spanning tree protocol parameters. A profile can be used on a per-VLAN basis. This octet String with 4096 octets maps VLANs to spanning tree protocol profiles: one octet containing the sheMstpBridgeProtoParamIndex per VLAN. The octet number is the sheVlanIndex. You can assign a VLAN to only one spanning-tree instance at a time. parameter of - modifyMstpBaseConfIdVlanIdList

sheMstpBridgeProtoParamTable.name: sheMstpBridgeProtoParamTable
sheMstpBridgeProtoParamTable.description: One table entry holds a profile of spanning tree protocol parameters. A profile can be used on a per-VLAN basis. The table has 32 static entries.

sheMstpBridgeProtoParamEntry.name: sheMstpBridgeProtoParamEntry
sheMstpBridgeProtoParamEntry.description: One table entry holds a profile of spanning tree protocol parameters. A profile can be used on a per-VLAN basis. The table has 32 static entries. Note that each MST region can only support up to 16 spanning-tree instances.

sheMstpBridgeProtoParamIndex.name: sheMstpBridgeProtoParamIndex
sheMstpBridgeProtoParamIndex.description: The primary key for the table. One table entry holds a profile of spanning tree protocol parameters. A profile can be used on a per-VLAN basis. The table has 32 static entries.

sheMstpBridgeProtoParamBridgeId.name: sheMstpBridgeProtoParamBridgeId
sheMstpBridgeProtoParamBridgeId.description: Each switch has an unique 8-byte bridge identifier (bridge ID), which determines the selection of the root switch. The two most-significant bytes are used for the switch priority, and the remaining six bytes are derived from the switch base MAC address.

sheMstpBridgeProtoParamBridgePriority.name: sheMstpBridgeProtoParamBridgePriority
sheMstpBridgeProtoParamBridgePriority.description: Each switch has an unique 8-byte bridge identifier (bridge ID), which determines the selection of the root switch. The two most-significant bytes are used for the switch priority, and the remaining six bytes are derived from the switch base MAC address. When you change the switch priority value, you change the probability that the switch will be elected as the root switch. Configuring a higher value decreases the probability; a lower value increases the probability. The configured value for the MstpBridgeProtoParamPriority should be completed by a fixed offsett, depending on the Mstp-Instance ID. That means, a configured priority-value of 4097 is valid for Mstp instance 1. Instance 2 will use 4098 in that case and instance 32 will have a MstpBridgeProtoParamPriority of 4128. Default value should be 32769 for MSTP-Instance 1 and 32800 for instance 32.

sheMstpBridgeProtoParamTcTime.name: sheMstpBridgeProtoParamTcTime
sheMstpBridgeProtoParamTcTime.description: The time since the last topology change.

sheMstpBridgeProtoParamTcCount.name: sheMstpBridgeProtoParamTcCount
sheMstpBridgeProtoParamTcCount.description: The total number of topology changes detected by this bridge since the management entity was last reset or initialized.

sheMstpBridgeProtoParamTc.name: sheMstpBridgeProtoParamTc
sheMstpBridgeProtoParamTc.description: A topology change has been detected.

sheMstpBridgeProtoParamDesignatedRoot.name: sheMstpBridgeProtoParamDesignatedRoot
sheMstpBridgeProtoParamDesignatedRoot.description: One switch in the network is elected as the root switch of the spanning tree by the Spanning Tree Protocol. The unique 8-byte bridge identifier (bridge ID) of the designated root switch as executed by this node. The two most-significant bytes are used for the switch priority, and the remaining six bytes are derived from the switch base MAC address. This value is used as the Root Identifier parameter in all Configuration Bridge PDUs originated by this node.

sheMstpBridgeProtoParamRootPort.name: sheMstpBridgeProtoParamRootPort
sheMstpBridgeProtoParamRootPort.description: A root port is selected for each switch (except the root switch). This port provides the best path (lowest cost) when the switch forwards packets to the root switch. The designated port to the root bridge, identified by the sheBridgePortIndex.

sheMstpBridgeProtoParamRootPathCost.name: sheMstpBridgeProtoParamRootPathCost
sheMstpBridgeProtoParamRootPathCost.description: The shortest distance to the root switch is calculated for each switch based on the path cost. Costs for the designated path to the root switch as seen from this switch.

sheMstpPortParamTable.name: sheMstpPortParamTable
sheMstpPortParamTable.description: The table holds the MSTP parameters on a per-port basis. The first key is a pointer to the MSTP profile equal to sheMstpBridgeProtoParamIndex (32 static entries). The second key is a pointer to the port equal to sheBridgePortIndex. There is a static entry for every possible MSTP port. That means 8 Ethernet uplink interfaces with redundundancy or 4 Ethernet uplink interfaces without redundundancy + 2 LAG ports.

sheMstpPortParamEntry.name: sheMstpPortParamEntry
sheMstpPortParamEntry.description: The table holds the MSTP parameters on a per-port basis. A free running index is used as key. There is a pointer to the MSTP profile equal to sheMstpBridgeProtoParamIndex (32 static entries). There is a seconde pointer to the port equal to sheBridgePortIndex. There is a static entry for every possible MSTP port. That means 8 Ethernet uplink interfaces with redundundancy or 4 Ethernet uplink interfaces without redundundancy + 2 LAG ports.

sheMstpPortParamTableIndex.name: sheMstpPortParamTableIndex
sheMstpPortParamTableIndex.description: A free running simple table index.

sheMstpPortParamProtoIndex.name: sheMstpPortParamProtoIndex
sheMstpPortParamProtoIndex.description: The MSTP profile, the table entry is related to, is the first key of the table. This object points to the sheMstpBridgeProtoParamTable (same as sheMstpBridgeProtoParamIndex).

sheMstpPortParamPortIndex.name: sheMstpPortParamPortIndex
sheMstpPortParamPortIndex.description: The port, the table entry is related to, is the second key of the table. This object points to the sheBridgePortTable (same as sheBridgePortIndex).

sheMstpPortParamUpTime.name: sheMstpPortParamUpTime
sheMstpPortParamUpTime.description: The total time the port was in the forwarding state since the management entity was last reset or initialized.

sheMstpPortParamState.name: sheMstpPortParamState
sheMstpPortParamState.description: Each Layer 2 interface on a switch using spanning tree exists in one of these states: Blocking: The interface does not participate in frame forwarding. Listening: The first transitional state after the blocking state when the spanning tree determines that the interface should participate in frame forwarding. Learning: The interface prepares to participate in frame forwarding. Forwarding: The interface forwards frames. Disabled: The interface is not participating in spanning tree because of a shutdown port, no link on the port, or no spanning-tree instance running on the port.

sheMstpPortParamPortId.name: sheMstpPortParamPortId
sheMstpPortParamPortId.description: The parameter consists of two parts. One part bears a fixed relationship to the physical or logical support of the Port by real-world equipment; this part assures the uniqueness of the Port Identifier among the Ports of a single Bridge, and is a small integer assigned by the NE in the range from one upwards. The other part of the parameter allows adjustment of the priority of the Port and is taken as the more significant part in priority comparisons. The priority part of this parameter can be updated by management.

sheMstpPortParamPortPriority.name: sheMstpPortParamPortPriority
sheMstpPortParamPortPriority.description: When two interfaces on a switch are part of a loop, the spanning-tree port priority and path cost settings determine which interface is put in the forwarding state and which is put in the blocking state. The port priority value represents the location of an interface in the network topology and how well it is located to pass traffic. For priority, the range is 0 to 240. The default is 128. The lower the number, the higher the priority.

sheMstpPortParamAdminPathCost.name: sheMstpPortParamAdminPathCost
sheMstpPortParamAdminPathCost.description: When two interfaces on a switch are part of a loop, the spanning-tree port priority and path cost settings determine which interface is put in the forwarding state and which is put in the blocking state. The path cost value represents media speed. A lower path cost represents higher-speed transmission. For cost, the range is 0 to 200000000; the default value is derived from the media speed of the interface. 1000 Mbps: 4. 100 Mbps: 19. 10 Mbps: 100. 0 means auto selection by the system.

sheMstpPortParamDesignatedRoot.name: sheMstpPortParamDesignatedRoot
sheMstpPortParamDesignatedRoot.description: One switch in the network is elected as the root switch of the spanning tree by the Spanning Tree Protocol. The unique 8-byte bridge identifier (bridge ID) of the designated root switch as executed by this node. The two most-significant bytes are used for the switch priority, and the remaining six bytes are derived from the switch base MAC address. This value is used as the Root Identifier parameter in all Configuration Bridge PDUs originated by this node.

sheMstpPortParamDesignatedBridge.name: sheMstpPortParamDesignatedBridge
sheMstpPortParamDesignatedBridge.description: A designated switch for each LAN segment is selected. The designated switch incurs the lowest path cost when forwarding packets from that LAN to the root switch. The port through which the designated switch is attached to the LAN is called the designated port.

sheMstpPortParamDesignatedPort.name: sheMstpPortParamDesignatedPort
sheMstpPortParamDesignatedPort.description: The port identifier of the port that transmitted a BPDU to me.

sheMstpPortParamDesignatedCost.name: sheMstpPortParamDesignatedCost
sheMstpPortParamDesignatedCost.description: A designated switch for each LAN segment is selected. The designated switch incurs the lowest path cost when forwarding packets from that LAN to the root switch. The port through which the designated switch is attached to the LAN is called the designated port. Costs for the designated path to the designated switch.

sheMstpPortParamPortRole.name: sheMstpPortParamPortRole
sheMstpPortParamPortRole.description: The RSTP provides rapid convergence of the spanning tree by assigning one of these port roles to individual ports and by determining the active topology. Root port Provides the best path (lowest cost) when the switch forwards packets to the root switch. Designated port Connects to the designated switch, which incurs the lowest path cost when forwarding packets from that LAN to the root switch. The port through which the designated switch is attached to the LAN is called the designated port. Alternate port Offers an alternate path toward the root switch to that provided by the current root port. Backup port Acts as a backup for the path provided by a designated port toward the leaves of the spanning tree. A backup port can exist only when two ports are connected together in a loopback by a point-to-point link or when a switch has two or more connections to a shared LAN segment. Disabled port Has no role within the operation of the spanning tree. A port with the root or a designated port role is included in the active topology. A port with the alternate or backup port role is excluded from the active topology.

sheMstpPortParamCurrentPathCost.name: sheMstpPortParamCurrentPathCost
sheMstpPortParamCurrentPathCost.description: These value represent the current pathcost value for this port.

Values : idle, busy, passed, failed. idle: default, no command in process busy: command execution in process, attempts to start another user command on this control block are rejected passed/failed: status at end of command

sheMstpControlTimestamp.description: Time stamp attribute set at the end of a command.

sheMstpControlTimer.name: sheMstpControlTimer
sheMstpControlTimer.description: Maximum command execution time (timeout) in seconds in case of a long running command.

sheMstpControlBridgeProtoParamIndex.name: sheMstpControlBridgeProtoParamIndex
sheMstpControlBridgeProtoParamIndex.description: Selects a table entry that holds a profile of spanning tree protocol parameters. A profile can be used on a per-VLAN basis. Parameter for - resetMstpTc - modifyMstpBridgeParamEntry

sheMstpControlBridgeProtoParamBridgePrio.name: sheMstpControlBridgeProtoParamBridgePriority
sheMstpControlBridgeProtoParamBridgePrio.description: Each switch has an unique 8-byte bridge identifier (bridge ID), which determines the selection of the root switch. The two most-significant bytes are used for the switch priority, and the remaining six bytes are derived from the switch base MAC address. When you change the switch priority value, you change the probability that the switch will be elected as the root switch. Configuring a higher value decreases the probability; a lower value increases the probability. Parameter for - modifyMstpBridgeParamEntry

sheMstpControlPortParamTableIndex.name: sheMstpControlPortParamTableIndex
sheMstpControlPortParamTableIndex.description: A free running simple table index.

sheMstpControlPortParamPortPriority.name: sheMstpControlPortParamPortPriority
sheMstpControlPortParamPortPriority.description: When two interfaces on a switch are part of a loop, the spanning-tree port priority and path cost settings determine which interface is put in the forwarding state and which is put in the blocking state. The port priority value represents the location of an interface in the network topology and how well it is located to pass traffic. For priority, the range is 0 to 240. The default is 128. The lower the number, the higher the priority. parameter for - modifyMstpPortParamEntry

sheMstpControlPortParamAdminPathCost.name: sheMstpControlPortParamAdminPathCost
sheMstpControlPortParamAdminPathCost.description: When two interfaces on a switch are part of a loop, the spanning-tree port priority and path cost settings determine which interface is put in the forwarding state and which is put in the blocking state. The path cost value represents media speed. A lower path cost represents higher-speed transmission. For cost, the range is 0 to 200000000; the default value is derived from the media speed of the interface. 1000 Mbps: 4. 100 Mbps: 19. 10 Mbps: 100. 0 means auto selection by the system. parameter for - modifyMstpPortParamEntry

sheCistBridgeProtoParamBridgeId.name: sheCistBridgeProtoParamBridgeId
sheCistBridgeProtoParamBridgeId.description: Each switch has an unique 8-byte bridge identifier (bridge ID), which determines the selection of the root switch. The two most-significant bytes are used for the switch priority, and the remaining six bytes are derived from the switch base MAC address.

sheCistBridgeProtoParamBridgePriority.name: sheCistBridgeProtoParamBridgePriority
sheCistBridgeProtoParamBridgePriority.description: Each switch has an unique 8-byte bridge identifier (bridge ID), which determines the selection of the root switch. The two most-significant bytes are used for the switch priority, and the remaining six bytes are derived from the switch base MAC address. When you change the switch priority value, you change the probability that the switch will be elected as the root switch. Configuring a higher value decreases the probability; a lower value increases the probability.

sheCistBridgeProtoParamTcTime.name: sheCistBridgeProtoParamTcTime
sheCistBridgeProtoParamTcTime.description: The time since the last topology change.

sheCistBridgeProtoParamTcCount.name: sheCistBridgeProtoParamTcCount
sheCistBridgeProtoParamTcCount.description: The total number of topology changes detected by this bridge since the management entity was last reset or initialized.

sheCistBridgeProtoParamTc.name: sheCistBridgeProtoParamTc
sheCistBridgeProtoParamTc.description: A topology change has been detected.

sheCistBridgeProtoParamDesignatedRoot.name: sheCistBridgeProtoParamDesignatedRoot
sheCistBridgeProtoParamDesignatedRoot.description: One switch in the network is elected as the root switch of the spanning tree by the Spanning Tree Protocol. The unique 8-byte bridge identifier (bridge ID) of the designated root switch as executed by this node. The two most-significant bytes are used for the switch priority, and the remaining six bytes are derived from the switch base MAC address. This value is used as the Root Identifier parameter in all Configuration Bridge PDUs originated by this node.

sheCistBridgeProtoParamRootPort.name: sheCistBridgeProtoParamRootPort
sheCistBridgeProtoParamRootPort.description: A root port is selected for each switch (except the root switch). This port provides the best path (lowest cost) when the switch forwards packets to the root switch. The designated port to the root bridge, identified by the sheBridgePortIndex.

sheCistBridgeProtoParamRootPathCost.name: sheCistBridgeProtoParamRootPathCost
sheCistBridgeProtoParamRootPathCost.description: The shortest distance to the root switch is calculated for each switch based on the path cost. Costs for the designated path to the root switch as seen from this switch.

sheCistBridgeProtoParamMaxAge.name: sheCistBridgeProtoParamMaxAge
sheCistBridgeProtoParamMaxAge.description: The maximum age of spanning tree protocol information learned from the network on any port before it is discarded (time a bridge port saves its configuration BPDU information), in units of hundredths of a second. This is the actual value that this bridge is currently using. This is 20 seconds by default and can be tuned to be between six and 40 seconds.

sheCistBridgeProtoParamHoldTime.name: sheCistBridgeProtoParamHoldTime
sheCistBridgeProtoParamHoldTime.description: This time value determines the interval length during which no more than two Configuration bridge PDUs shall be transmitted by this node, in units of hundredths of a second.

sheCistBridgeProtoParamForwardDelay.name: sheCistBridgeProtoParamForwardDelay
sheCistBridgeProtoParamForwardDelay.description: This time value, measured in units of hundredths of a second, controls how fast a port changes its spanning state when moving towards the Forwarding state. The value determines how long the port stays in each of the Listening and Learning states, which precede the Forwarding state. This value is also used, when a topology change has been detected and is underway, to age all dynamic entries in the Forwarding Database. [Note that this value is the one that this bridge is currently using, in contrast to dot1dStpBridgeForwardDelay which is the value that this bridge and all others would start using if/when this bridge were to become the root.] This is by default equal to 15 seconds, but can be tuned to be between four and 30 seconds.

sheCistBridgeProtoParamBridgeMaxAge.name: sheCistBridgeProtoParamBridgeMaxAge
sheCistBridgeProtoParamBridgeMaxAge.description: The value that all bridges use for MaxAge when this bridge is acting as the root in units of hundredths of a second. Note that 802.1D-1990 specifies that the range for this parameter is related to the value of dot1dStpBridgeHelloTime. The granularity of this timer is specified by 802.1D-1990 to be 1 second. An agent may return a badValue error if a set is attempted to a value which is not a whole number of seconds.

sheCistBridgeProtoParamBridgeHelloTime.name: sheCistBridgeProtoParamBridgeHelloTime
sheCistBridgeProtoParamBridgeHelloTime.description: The value that all bridges use for HelloTime when this bridge is acting as the root in units of hundredths of a second. The hello time is the time between each Bridge Protocol Data Unit (BPDU) that is sent on a port. This is equal to two seconds by default, but can be tuned to be between one and ten seconds. The granularity of this timer is specified by 802.1D-1990 to be 1 second. An agent may return a badValue error if a set is attempted to a value which is not a whole number of seconds.

sheCistBridgeProtoParamBridgeForwardDela.name: sheCistBridgeProtoParamBridgeForwardDelay
sheCistBridgeProtoParamBridgeForwardDela.description: The value that all bridges use for ForwardDelay when this bridge is acting as the root. Note that 802.1D-1990 specifies that the range for this parameter is related to the value of BridgeMaxAge. This time value, measured in units of hundredths of a second, controls how fast a port changes its spanning state when moving towards the Forwarding state. The value determines how long the port stays in each of the Listening and Learning states, which precede the Forwarding state. This value is also used, when a topology change has been detected and is underway, to age all dynamic entries in the Forwarding Database. The granularity of this timer is specified by 802.1D-1990 to be 1 second. An agent may return a badValue error if a set is attempted to a value which is not a whole number of seconds. This is by default equal to 15 seconds, but can be tuned to be between four and 30 seconds.

sheCistBridgeProtoParamForceVer.name: sheCistBridgeProtoParamForceVer
sheCistBridgeProtoParamForceVer.description: When RSTP is configuring or reconfiguring the network, there is an increased and implementation dependent probability that frames that are in transit will be misordered or duplicated as network paths change, since a Bridge can buffer frames awaiting transmission through its Ports. Some LAN protocols, for example, LLC Type 2, are particularly sensitive to frame misordering and duplication; to support these the Force Protocol Version parameter can be used to delay the transition of ports to a Forwarding state and further reduce the probability of such events. The Force Protocol Version parameter for the Bridge can take the value 0 (STP Compatibility mode),2 (the default, normal operation) or 3 (MSTP Compatibility).

sheCistBridgeProtoParamRegionalRootId.name: sheCistBridgeProtoParamRegionalRootId
sheCistBridgeProtoParamRegionalRootId.description: One switch in the network is elected as the root switch of the spanning tree by the Spanning Tree Protocol. The unique 8-byte bridge identifier (bridge ID) of the designated root switch as executed by this node. The two most-significant bytes are used for the switch priority, and the remaining six bytes are derived from the switch base MAC address. This value is used as the Root Identifier parameter in all Configuration Bridge PDUs originated by this node.

sheCistBridgeProtoParamRegionalRootPathC.name: sheCistBridgeProtoParamRegionalRootPathCost
sheCistBridgeProtoParamRegionalRootPathC.description: The shortest distance to the root switch is calculated for each switch based on the path cost. Costs for the designated path to the root switch as seen from this switch.

sheCistBridgeProtoParamMaxHops.name: sheCistBridgeProtoParamMaxHops
sheCistBridgeProtoParamMaxHops.description: Number of possible hops in the region. Only used if forcedVersion = mstp(3).

sheCistBridgeProtoParamSelfLoopDetect.name: sheCistBridgeProtoParamSelfLoopDetect
sheCistBridgeProtoParamSelfLoopDetect.description: Enable/Disable the stp self loop detection.

sheCistPortParamTable.name: sheCistPortParamTable
sheCistPortParamTable.description: The table holds the CIST parameters on a per-port basis. The key is a pointer to the port equal to sheBridgePortIndex. There is a static entry for every possible MSTP port. That means 8 Ethernet uplink interfaces with redundundancy or 4 Ethernet uplink interfaces without redundundancy + 2 LAG ports.

sheCistPortParamEntry.name: sheCistPortParamEntry
sheCistPortParamEntry.description: The table holds the CIST parameters on a per-port basis. The key is a pointer to the port equal to sheBridgePortIndex. There is a static entry for every possible MSTP port. That means 8 Ethernet uplink interfaces with redundundancy or 4 Ethernet uplink interfaces without redundundancy + 2 LAG ports.

sheCistPortParamIndex.name: sheCistPortParamIndex
sheCistPortParamIndex.description: That is the sheBridgePortIndex of the corresponding BridgePort.

sheCistPortParamUpTime.name: sheCistPortParamUpTime
sheCistPortParamUpTime.description: The total time the port was in the forwarding state since the management entity was last reset or initialized.

sheCistPortParamState.name: sheCistPortParamState
sheCistPortParamState.description: Each Layer 2 interface on a switch using spanning tree exists in one of these states: Blocking: The interface does not participate in frame forwarding. Listening: The first transitional state after the blocking state when the spanning tree determines that the interface should participate in frame forwarding. Learning: The interface prepares to participate in frame forwarding. Forwarding: The interface forwards frames. Disabled: The interface is not participating in spanning tree because of a shutdown port, no link on the port, or no spanning-tree instance running on the port.

sheCistPortParamPortId.name: sheCistPortParamPortId
sheCistPortParamPortId.description: The parameter consists of two parts. One part bears a fixed relationship to the physical or logical support of the Port by real-world equipment; this part assures the uniqueness of the Port Identifier among the Ports of a single Bridge, and is a small integer assigned by the NE in the range from one upwards. The other part of the parameter allows adjustment of the priority of the Port and is taken as the more significant part in priority comparisons. The priority part of this parameter can be updated by management.

sheCistPortParamPortPriority.name: sheCistPortParamPortPriority
sheCistPortParamPortPriority.description: When two interfaces on a switch are part of a loop, the spanning-tree port priority and path cost settings determine which interface is put in the forwarding state and which is put in the blocking state. The port priority value represents the location of an interface in the network topology and how well it is located to pass traffic. For priority, the range is 0 to 240. The default is 128. The lower the number, the higher the priority.

sheCistPortParamAdminPathCost.name: sheCistPortParamAdminPathCost
sheCistPortParamAdminPathCost.description: When two interfaces on a switch are part of a loop, the spanning-tree port priority and path cost settings determine which interface is put in the forwarding state and which is put in the blocking state. The path cost value represents media speed. A lower path cost represents higher-speed transmission. For cost, the range is 1 to 200000000; the default value is derived from the media speed of the interface. 1000 Mbps: 4. 100 Mbps: 19. 10 Mbps: 100. 0 means auto selection by the system.

sheCistPortParamDesignatedRoot.name: sheCistPortParamDesignatedRoot
sheCistPortParamDesignatedRoot.description: One switch in the network is elected as the root switch of the spanning tree by the Spanning Tree Protocol. The unique 8-byte bridge identifier (bridge ID) of the designated root switch as executed by this node. The two most-significant bytes are used for the switch priority, and the remaining six bytes are derived from the switch base MAC address. This value is used as the Root Identifier parameter in all Configuration Bridge PDUs originated by this node.

sheCistPortParamDesignatedCost.name: sheCistPortParamDesignatedCost
sheCistPortParamDesignatedCost.description: A designated switch for each LAN segment is selected. The designated switch incurs the lowest path cost when forwarding packets from that LAN to the root switch. The port through which the designated switch is attached to the LAN is called the designated port. Costs for the designated path to the designated switch.

sheCistPortParamDesignatedBridge.name: sheCistPortParamDesignatedBridge
sheCistPortParamDesignatedBridge.description: A designated switch for each LAN segment is selected. The designated switch incurs the lowest path cost when forwarding packets from that LAN to the root switch. The port through which the designated switch is attached to the LAN is called the designated port.

sheCistPortParamDesignatedPort.name: sheCistPortParamDesignatedPort
sheCistPortParamDesignatedPort.description: The port identifier of the port that transmitted a BPDU to me.

sheCistPortParamTcAck.name: sheCistPortParamTcAck
sheCistPortParamTcAck.description: A boolean. Set if a Configuration Message with a topology change acknowledge flag set is to be transmitted.

sheCistPortParamAdminEdgePort.name: sheCistPortParamAdminEdgePort
sheCistPortParamAdminEdgePort.description: Port can be configured to be an edge port.

sheCistPortParamOperEdgePort.name: sheCistPortParamOperEdgePort
sheCistPortParamOperEdgePort.description: If port is configured to be an edge port, in the absence of a received BPDU, this port is identified as an operEdgePort.

sheCistPortParamMacEnabled.name: sheCistPortParamMacEnabled
sheCistPortParamMacEnabled.description: The value of this parameter is TRUE if use of the MAC entity is permitted; and is otherwise FALSE.

sheCistPortParamMacOperational.name: sheCistPortParamMacOperational
sheCistPortParamMacOperational.description: The value of this parameter is TRUE if the MAC entity is in a functioning state; i.e., the MAC entity can be used to transmit and/or receive frames, and its use is permitted by management. Its value is otherwise FALSE.

sheCistPortParamAdminPointToPointMac.name: sheCistPortParamAdminPointToPointMac
sheCistPortParamAdminPointToPointMac.description: This parameter can take three values: a) ForceTrue. The administrator requires the MAC to be treated as if it is connected to a point-to-point LAN. b) ForceFalse. The administrator requires the MAC to be treated as connected to a non-point-to-point LAN. c) Auto. The administrator requires the point-to-point status of the MAC to be determined by specific MAC procedures.

sheCistPortParamOperPointToPointMac.name: sheCistPortParamOperPointToPointMac
sheCistPortParamOperPointToPointMac.description: TRUE, if the MAC is connected to a point-to-point LAN, otherwise FALSE.

sheCistPortParamRegionalRootId.name: sheCistPortParamRegionalRootId
sheCistPortParamRegionalRootId.description: The CIST Regional Root is the bridge of this region that has the lowest External Root Path Cost through a Boundary Port.

sheCistPortParamRegionalRootPathCost.name: sheCistPortParamRegionalRootPathCost
sheCistPortParamRegionalRootPathCost.description: Path cost to the CIST Regional Root, the bridge of this region that has the lowest External Root Path Cost through a Boundary Port.

sheCistPortParamPortHelloTime.name: sheCistPortParamPortHelloTime
sheCistPortParamPortHelloTime.description: The hello time actual used by that port.

sheCistPortParamHelloTime.name: sheCistPortParamHelloTime
sheCistPortParamHelloTime.description: The time interval between the generation of Configuration BPDUs by the Root.

sheCistPortParamPortRole.name: sheCistPortParamPortRole
sheCistPortParamPortRole.description: The RSTP provides rapid convergence of the spanning tree by assigning one of these port roles to individual ports and by determining the active topology. Root port Provides the best path (lowest cost) when the switch forwards packets to the root switch. Designated port Connects to the designated switch, which incurs the lowest path cost when forwarding packets from that LAN to the root switch. The port through which the designated switch is attached to the LAN is called the designated port. Alternate port Offers an alternate path toward the root switch to that provided by the current root port. Backup port Acts as a backup for the path provided by a designated port toward the leaves of the spanning tree. A backup port can exist only when two ports are connected together in a loopback by a point-to-point link or when a switch has two or more connections to a shared LAN segment. Disabled port Has no role within the operation of the spanning tree. A port with the root or a designated port role is included in the active topology. A port with the alternate or backup port role is excluded from the active topology.

sheCistPortParamLoopDetect.name: sheCistPortParamLoopDetect
sheCistPortParamLoopDetect.description: The current loop detect state. Note: Only supported by hix5608 R1.3!!

sheCistControlRequest.name: sheCistControlRequest
sheCistControlRequest.description: A SetRequest on this attribute starts a command execution process in the NetElement. sheCistBridgeProtoParam - resetCistTc parameters: 'no' - modifyCistBridgeParameters parameters: sheCistControlBridgeProtoParamBridgePriority sheCistControlBridgeProtoParamBridgeMaxAge sheCistControlBridgeProtoParamBridgeHelloTime sheCistControlBridgeProtoParamBridgeForwardDelay sheCistControlBridgeProtoParamForceVer sheCistControlBridgeProtoParamMaxHops sheCistControlBridgeProtoParamSelfLoopDetect sheCistPortParamTable - modifyCistPortParamEntry parameters: sheCistControlPortParamIndex sheCistControlPortParamPortPriority sheCistControlPortParamAdminPathCost sheCistControlPortParamAdminEdgePort sheCistControlPortParamMacEnabled sheCistControlPortParamAdminPointToPointMac

sheCistControlStatus.description: Describes the status of a user command group, used for block commands while a command execution is in process. Values : idle, busy, passed, failed. idle: default, no command in process busy: command execution in process, attempts to start another user command on this control block are rejected passed/failed: status at end of command

sheCistControlTimestamp.name: sheCistControlTimestamp
sheCistControlTimestamp.description: Time stamp attribute set at the end of a command.

sheCistControlTimer.name: sheCistControlTimer
sheCistControlTimer.description: Maximum command execution time (timeout) in seconds in case of a long running command.

sheCistControlBridgeProtoParamBridgePrio.description: Each switch has an unique 8-byte bridge identifier (bridge ID), which determines the selection of the root switch. The two most-significant bytes are used for the switch priority, and the remaining six bytes are derived from the switch base MAC address. When you change the switch priority value, you change the probability that the switch will be elected as the root switch. Configuring a higher value decreases the probability; a lower value increases the probability. parameter for - modifyCistBridgeParameters

sheCistControlBridgeProtoParamBridgeForw.description: The value that all bridges use for ForwardDelay when this bridge is acting as the root. sheCistControlBridgeProtoParamForceVer.name: sheCistControlBridgeProtoParamForceVer
sheCistControlBridgeProtoParamForceVer.description: When RSTP is configuring or reconfiguring the network, there is an increased and implementation dependent probability that frames that are in transit will be misordered or duplicated as network paths change, since a Bridge can buffer frames awaiting transmission through its Ports. Some LAN protocols, for example, LLC Type 2, are particularly sensitive to frame misordering and duplication; to support these the Force Protocol Version parameter can be used to delay the transition of ports to a Forwarding state and further reduce the probability of such events. The Force Protocol Version parameter for the Bridge can take the value 0 (STP Compatibility mode),2 (the default, normal operation). Third version is Mstp compatibility.

sheCistControlBridgeProtoParamMaxHops.name: sheCistControlBridgeProtoParamMaxHops
sheCistControlBridgeProtoParamMaxHops.description: Number of possible hops in the region. Only used if forcedVersion = mstp(3).

sheCistControlBridgeProtoParamSelfLoopDe.name: sheCistControlBridgeProtoParamSelfLoopDetect
sheCistControlBridgeProtoParamSelfLoopDe.description: Enable/Disable the stp self loop detection.

sheCistControlPortParamIndex.description: Index of the sheCistPortParamTable entry to be modified. parameter for - modifyCistPortParamEntry
